I have used this app for about a year now for short personal travel films. FV-5 apps are marketed to consumers that want a specific look but dont want to be limited by a bulky DSLR or camcorder. These end users want to be different. They want that unique shot. The amount of custom settings is astounding. I love the ability to change pretty much all of my visual settings at a flick of the thumbs. White balance, ISO, focus, it's all there. Although it is already super versatile it is somewhat limiting. I would love to see more special features in the coming updates.  1) HIGHER FRAME RATE: To my knowledge, through playing with the settings and reading the user manual, the app is limited to 30fps. I have lowered my resolution setting hoping to open up higher frame rates but no dice. For an app with a name that alludes to being cinematic this is a big limitation. 2) TIME LAPS: This is a common cinematic feature that many film makers and travelers want to have in their bag of tools.  Great app! I love the FV-5 apps and I will continue to refer others to this app. Unfortunately for now I need to switch between apps for specific cinematic features.

If you were wondering why it wont record to your SD card. If you are on Android 5 and up... you must copy all your data off your SD card and format the SD card in the phone. Formatting the SD card on a PC  or Mac wont work, it must be done in the phone!!! The you must create a folder, say "my videos" on the SD card and tell the program to store video files there. You will be asked to assign a writable folder, point to that folder Now it writes to SD card. Simple.

Works great on my LG Gpad 7.0. As a professional videographer, I like the historgram and audio levels features, and these advancements, as well as the ISO level controls, make this app a cut above any other video apps I've used, including the stock camera app that came on the GPad. One minor thing I don't like, however, is that the controls along the bottom of the app are perilously close to the touch-sensitive controls on the GPad, the ones that return to the Home Screen, and the on-screen Back Button. One thing I can offer other users that were initially having white balance troubles when first starting out with this app: Hold a white piece of paper, or face the back of some person wearing a white t-shirt, get the white in the entire frame and then select average white balance on the white balance controls. You'll get a great looking color rendition in your video. Also, if you edit video externally from your tablet or phone running the app, go into the settings controls and turn the sharpening to about 50%, then add sharpening when you edit.

*** PROS ***  - Most apps stop recording at 30 minutes. This app automatically starts recording a new file - As far as I know this is the only camera app that will do that. I need to record something that went on for more than an hour, so I was ecstatic when I found this app.    ** CONS *** Can't record to SD card in 4.4.  The dev points to the change in Android that prevents apps from writing to the SD card. The change only prevents apps from writing to "anywhere" on the SD card. Apps can still write to their application specific folder. For some reason they haven't implemented this.   I was really angry that I found an app that can record for more than thirty minutes, but couldn't use it because I didn't have enough free space.   I ended up using a 4.3 phone. I know Android storage is a mess in general and really bad with the big changes in 4.4 and 5.0, but there is a mechanism - Writing to the app specific folder - and they need to use it, otherwise this app is useless with 4.4 phones.

replyContent: We imagine the problem arises when trying to write to the external SD card. Unfortunately, no app can write to the SD card under Android 4.4. Even on Android 5, there are some internal restrictions, and when possible, writing the SD card is much slower than before, and for video is a big issue. That's the reason we can't support the SD card now...

replyContent: The app is meant for recording using the device *own* camera, not for transferring old movies. By the way, if you do want to set the frame rate for recording using the device's *own* camera, you can indeed do it, go to Settings / Video tab, activate "Custom video settings" option, then below set the option "Frame rate" to other than 30 FPS default.

content: Why does it say that it records in 2.1 megapixel when my camera is 8 megapixel? Why is 2.1 megapixel the highest setting when my camera can go up to 8 it's calling 2.1 megapixel full 1080 I don't understand why
replyContent: Cinema FV-5 does video recording, not still photo taking. Your sensor is capable of taking 8 MP still photos, but video recording maxes out at 1080p Full HD, which if you calculate the amount of pixels per frame, equates to 2.1 MP. Don't be distracted by this number: your camera records at 1080p, which is the current standard.
